> That's a BIG problem.

Would you be so kind as to formulate the problem a little more specifically?

The first obstacle I see in implementing advanced keyboard protocols is that a GTK keyboard input event does not provide sufficient information to support protocols like kitty or, say, win32-input-mode ([spec](https://github.com/microsoft/terminal/blob/main/doc/specs/%234999%20-%20Improved%20keyboard%20handling%20in%20Conpty.md)). The win32-input-mode protocol, in my view, is relatively simple to implement yet powerful enough (e.g., it allows distinguishing between the right and left Control keys, something the kitty protocol cannot do). Therefore, I decided to start with it. I'll explain using this protocol as an example.

This is the structure of the ESC sequence for a win32-input-mode event:
```
^[ [ Vk ; Sc ; Uc ; Kd ; Cs ; Rc _
```

Vk: the value of wVirtualKeyCode — any number. If omitted, defaults to '0'.

Sc: the value of wVirtualScanCode — any number. If omitted, defaults to '0'.

Uc: the decimal value of UnicodeChar — for example, NUL is "0", LF is "10", the character 'A' is "65". If omitted, defaults to '0'.

Kd: the value of bKeyDown — either a '0' or '1'. If omitted, defaults to '0'.

Cs: the value of dwControlKeyState — any number. If omitted, defaults to '0'.

Rc: the value of wRepeatCount — any number. If omitted, defaults to '1'.

As we can see, the fields correspond to the KEY_EVENT_RECORD structure, which you can easily find in the [documentation](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/console/key-event-record-str).

The wVirtualScanCode is not a critically important parameter. Application developers generally do not use it, preferring the more portable wVirtualKeyCode instead. However, wVirtualScanCode is still necessary for distinguishing between the left and right Shift keys.

Accordingly, our interest lies in determining the correct value for [wVirtualKeyCode](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/inputdev/virtual-key-codes). This is where we encounter a problem: the Keyval value in a GTK event is tied to the current keyboard layout, whereas the wVirtualKeyCode is not. For a key with the Latin letter "A," wVirtualKeyCode will always equal 65 (0x41), even if the current layout is Russian, where this key generates the letter "Ф."

To solve this problem, we can use the xkbcommon library (it works with both X11 and Wayland). With its help, we can determine which character the given key would generate in the Latin layout by using the hardware key code field of the GTK event.

I want to note that knowing the Latin character corresponding to the current key, independent of the current layout, is also necessary for a full implementation of the extended terminal keyboard input protocol for kitty.

Here is a sample application demonstrating how this can be done. Here is the code:
```
#include <gtk/gtk.h>
#include <xkbcommon/xkbcommon.h>

// Structure for storing xkb state
typedef struct {
    struct xkb_context *context;
    struct xkb_keymap *keymap;
    struct xkb_state *state_english; // State for the English layout
} XkbData;

// Function for handling keyboard events
static gboolean on_key_event(GtkWidget *widget, GdkEventKey *event, gpointer data) {
    XkbData *xkb_data = (XkbData *)data;
    GtkTextBuffer *buffer = GTK_TEXT_BUFFER(g_object_get_data(G_OBJECT(widget), "buffer"));

    const char *event_type = (event->type == GDK_KEY_PRESS) ? "Key Press" : "Key Release";

    xkb_state_update_key(xkb_data->state_english, event->hardware_keycode, 
        (event->type == GDK_KEY_PRESS) ? XKB_KEY_DOWN : XKB_KEY_UP);

    // Get the key symbol
    xkb_keysym_t keysym = xkb_state_key_get_one_sym(xkb_data->state_english, event->hardware_keycode);

    // Get the symbol name
    char keysym_name[64];
    xkb_keysym_get_name(keysym, keysym_name, sizeof(keysym_name));

    // Get modifiers
    xkb_mod_mask_t mods = xkb_state_serialize_mods(xkb_data->state_english, XKB_STATE_MODS_DEPRESSED);

    // Get the key symbol for the English layout
    char text_english[64] = {0};
    xkb_state_key_get_utf8(xkb_data->state_english, event->hardware_keycode, text_english, sizeof(text_english));

    // Form the message

    gchar *message = g_strdup_printf(
        "Event: %s\nKeyval: %u (%s, %lc)\nHardware Keycode: %u\nGroup: %u\nModifiers: %u\nXKB Keysym: %s\nXKB text eng: %s\nXKB mods: %u\n\n",
        // XKB text cur: %s\n
        event_type,
        event->keyval,
        gdk_keyval_name(event->keyval),
        gdk_keyval_to_unicode(event->keyval),
        event->hardware_keycode,
        event->group,
        event->state,
        keysym_name[0] ? keysym_name : "Unknown",
        text_english[0] ? text_english : "None",
        mods
    );

    // Add text to the buffer
    GtkTextIter end;
    gtk_text_buffer_get_end_iter(buffer, &end);
    gtk_text_buffer_insert(buffer, &end, message, -1);

    g_free(message);
    return FALSE; // Continue processing other handlers
}

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    gtk_init(&argc, &argv);

    // Initialize xkb
    XkbData xkb_data = {0};
    xkb_data.context = xkb_context_new(XKB_CONTEXT_NO_FLAGS);
    if (!xkb_data.context) {
        g_error("Failed to create XKB context");
    }

    // Load the current keyboard layout
    struct xkb_rule_names names = {0}; // Use system settings
    xkb_data.keymap = xkb_keymap_new_from_names(xkb_data.context, &names, XKB_KEYMAP_COMPILE_NO_FLAGS);
    if (!xkb_data.keymap) {
        g_error("Failed to create XKB keymap");
    }

    // Create state for the English layout
    struct xkb_rule_names english_names = { .layout = "us" }; // Specify English layout
    struct xkb_keymap *english_keymap = xkb_keymap_new_from_names(xkb_data.context, &english_names, XKB_KEYMAP_COMPILE_NO_FLAGS);
    if (!english_keymap) {
        g_error("Failed to create XKB English keymap");
    }
    xkb_data.state_english = xkb_state_new(english_keymap);
    xkb_keymap_unref(english_keymap);

    // Create main window
    GtkWidget *window = gtk_window_new(GTK_WINDOW_TOPLEVEL);
    gtk_window_set_title(GTK_WINDOW(window), "Keyboard Event Viewer (Dual Layouts)");
    gtk_window_set_default_size(GTK_WINDOW(window), 600, 400);

    // Create text view
    GtkWidget *text_view = gtk_text_view_new();
    gtk_text_view_set_editable(GTK_TEXT_VIEW(text_view), FALSE);
    GtkTextBuffer *buffer = gtk_text_view_get_buffer(GTK_TEXT_VIEW(text_view));
    g_object_set_data(G_OBJECT(window), "buffer", buffer);

    // Add text view to scroll window
    GtkWidget *scrolled_window = gtk_scrolled_window_new(NULL, NULL);
    gtk_container_add(GTK_CONTAINER(scrolled_window), text_view);

    // Pack everything into the window
    gtk_container_add(GTK_CONTAINER(window), scrolled_window);

    // Connect signals
    g_signal_connect(window, "destroy", G_CALLBACK(gtk_main_quit), NULL);
    g_signal_connect(window, "key-press-event", G_CALLBACK(on_key_event), &xkb_data);
    g_signal_connect(window, "key-release-event", G_CALLBACK(on_key_event), &xkb_data);

    // Show the window
    gtk_widget_show_all(window);

    gtk_main();

    // Free resources
    xkb_state_unref(xkb_data.state_english);
    xkb_keymap_unref(xkb_data.keymap);
    xkb_context_unref(xkb_data.context);

    return 0;
}

